# Extractor rules

These functions turn media into features. They are the ONLY code allowed to
decode pixels or audio.

- Each extractor is a **pure function** `(path | frames) -> typed features`. No
  side effects, no writing files, no global state.
- Extractors **measure, they do not decide.** Pre-trained utility models (OCR,
  face detection, voice-activity / speech-to-text) are measurement instruments,
  not "the intelligence." Never let them choose edits — that belongs to the
  director, and only through the heuristic-or-LLM plan.
- The **same extractors serve Phase A (learning) and Phase B (editing).** Do not
  fork them per phase; point them at different inputs.
- Emit **per-shot records**:
  - Pacing: cut list, median shot length, motion curve (PySceneDetect + frame diff).
  - Framing: aspect ratio, face count/position, shot scale (`close` / `wide`).
  - Audio: BPM, beat times, RMS energy curve, `speech` vs `music` flag.
  - Text: on-screen text position, timing relative to cuts/speech, and **style
    class** (`karaoke` word-by-word vs `static` title) — NOT the exact font.
- Prefer `ffprobe` / `ffmpeg` / PySceneDetect over decoding frames in pure Python
  where possible (speed and memory).
- Every extractor has a unit test against a small fixture in `/fixtures`. Tests
  must NOT require rendering.
